，但没有提及制造过程。 To this day, many of the iconic instruments under the company&#39;s umbrella are manufactured in the USA, so we&#39;ll keep an eye on if that changes. Alesis, also owned by inMusic, designs its products in America but manufactures them in China.</p><p> There&#39;s also the idea of brand cross-pollination. In the announcement letter, Richardson says the acquisition will allow Moog to “enhance the capabilities of inMusic and its exclusive brands.” Does this suggest a future Moog synth with actual Akai MPC pads or a budget-friendly Alesis synthesizer that takes advantage of Moog&#39;s audio-shaping expertise?我们将会看到。 In the meantime, Moog just<ins> <a data-i13n="cpos:3;pos:1" href="https://www.engadget.com/moog-celebrates-70th-anniversary-with-musical-web-app-140043922.html">celebrated its 70th anniversary</a></ins> with a Model D-inspired web app and recently released the Moog One, its most ambitious (and expensive) instrument ever.</p> This article originally appeared on Engadget at https://www.engadget.com/moog-acquired-by-conglomerate-inmusic-joining-akai-and-alesis-164536639.html?src=rss]]>; </description><link/><![CDATA[https://www.engadget.com/moog-acquired-by-conglomerate-inmusic-joining-akai-and-alesis-164536639.html?src=rss]]><source_id> engadget_479</source_id><guid ispermalink="false"> b75a4d20-26fb-4ebe-8efe-0650b36aacf4</guid><dc:creator> Lawrence Bonk</dc:creator><source/><![CDATA[Engadget]]><dc:publisher> Engadget</dc:publisher><dc:rightsholder> Engadget</dc:rightsholder><pubDate> Tue, 13 Jun 2023 16:45:36 +0000</pubDate><ingested> 1686674146</ingested><modified> 2023-06-13T16:35:49+00:00 </modified><category><![CDATA[site|engadget]]></category><category><![CDATA[provider_name|Engadget]]></category><category><![CDATA[region|US]]></category><category><![CDATA[language|en-US]]></category><category><![CDATA[author_name|Lawrence Bonk]]></category><media:content height="1478" medium="image" url="https://s.yimg.com/os/creatr-uploaded-images/2023-06